qas.question: What mountains did the Australian battalions fight a rearguard action over on the Kokoda Track?

In 1942, what Australian Air Force base was attacked by Japanese marines?

context: Japanese land forces continued to advance in the Solomon Islands and New Guinea. From July 1942, a few Australian reserve battalions, many of them very young and untrained, fought a stubborn rearguard action in New Guinea, against a Japanese advance along the Kokoda Track, towards Port Moresby, over the rugged <a0_0>Owen Stanley Ranges<a0_0/>. The militia, worn out and severely depleted by casualties, were relieved in late August by regular troops from the <a1_0>Second Australian Imperial Force<a1_0/>, returning from action in the <a4_0>Mediterranean<a4_0/> theater. In early September 1942 Japanese marines attacked a strategic Royal Australian Air Force base at <a2_0>Milne Bay<a2_0/>, near the <a3_0>eastern tip<a3_0/> of New Guinea. They were beaten back by Allied (primarily Australian Army) forces.
